Registered: Jun 28, 1999Posts: 14851
Posted: Tue Mar 13, 2012 10:06 am
topham wrote:It doesn't mean that your odds are better if you use a stupid method.No, that isn't evidence for why stupid is better, but there is logic to why stupid methods do better:1) The tournament is so large that unpredictable results are the norm, not the exception.2) Intelligent methods assume predictable results, which are very unlikely to happen.3) Intelligent methods tend to come up with similar predictions than other intelligent methods, and therefore, if they win are more likely to have others win as well, and then winning the tie-breaker is required, which lowers the likelihood of winning.4) By going stupid, you have the best chance of being the only person with your predictions, which means that if you win, you win outright, and your tie-breaker is irrelevant. 5) You are more likely to accidentally predict big upsets that actually occur than people who pick intelligently. Most systems give bonuses for correctly predicting underdogs. (E.G. In ours, in the first two rounds, you get to add the seed of predicted team to your point total if you win, so correctly predicting a #16 seed team to win gets you 16 bonus points.) If you predict the #64 team to win the first 2 rounds (and they do) you get big, big points.
