Posted: Tue Mar 13, 2012 12:43 pm
While picking an upset correctly will generally add massive amounts of points to your scores, there are some more logic based things you can do with a little research.1. Preseason rankings will (barring significant injuries) give you a good idea of how good a team is on paper. Useful for tie breaking picks between two similarly ranked teams.2. Teams that have to travel less are more likely to win against equal teams.2a. To a lesser extent, teams that travel well - these would be big name teams that can make any game seem like a home game if it's on neutral territory. Duke for example.3. Teams that finish the regular and conference tournaments hot (last year's tournament is a great example of this) seem to be more likely to win.4. Barring upsets, small name teams seem to be less likely to win. The lower seeds are more likely to have to travel and won't get much support outside of their home area. For example, Temple is basically the only Philadelphia area team and I expect that they will get minimal road support.
